    {
      "title": "Noble Gases",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Group 18 (The Noble Gases)</strong></h3><ul><li>Because of highest ionisation energy of group 18 elements in their respective periods, they were given the name 'noble gases' and thus inert. However, at least in the case of xenon, it is not so; it forms series of compounds.</li><li>The noble gases are colourless, tasteless and odourless. In the liquid and solid states the only forces of attraction among the atoms are very weak London or van der Waals forces. Polarisability and interatomic interactions increase with increasing atomic number. The attractive forces among the atoms are so small that they remain liquid at 1 atmospheric pressure even at a temperature of $0.001~\\text{K}$.</li><li>Helium has the lowest boiling point of any element, and its behaviour as a liquid is most unusual. It will creep up the walls of the container in which it is placed and thus it exists in two phases in liquid helium, one of which has an extremely low viscosity.</li></ul>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dccdc03b9dcaf1afe7c5"
    },
    {
      "title": "Xenon Fluorides",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Xenon fluorides</strong></h3><p>Xenon reacts directly with fluorine (only). The products depend on respective amounts of Xe and ${{\\text{F}}_{2}}$ and temperature also. The reactions are generally carried out in seal tubes.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p>$\\Delta \\to \\text{ heart}$</p><p>$\\text{P}\\to \\text{ Pressure}$</p><p>These three fluorides are crystalline volatile substances which sublime at room temperature but can be kept in nickel containers.</p><p>The fluorides are strong oxidising agents.</p><p>$\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{2}}+2\\text{HCl}\\xrightarrow{{}}\\text{Xe}+\\text{C}{{\\text{l}}_{2}}+2\\text{HF}$</p><p>$\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{4}}+4\\text{KI}\\xrightarrow[{}]{}\\text{Xe}+2{{\\text{I}}_{2}}+4\\text{KF}$</p><p>$\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{2}}+\\text{C}{{\\text{e}}_{2}}{{\\left( \\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}} \\right)}_{3}}+\\text{SO}_{4}^{2-}\\xrightarrow{{}}\\text{Xe}+2\\text{Ce}{{\\left( \\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}} \\right)}_{2}}+{{\\text{F}}_{2}}$</p><p>They are good fluorinating agents also.</p><p>$2\\text{S}{{\\text{F}}_{4}}+\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{4}}\\xrightarrow{{}}2\\text{S}{{\\text{F}}_{6}}+\\text{Xe}$</p><p>$\\text{Pt}+\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{4}}\\xrightarrow{{}}\\text{Pt}{{\\text{F}}_{4}}+\\text{Xe}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p>Their reaction with water is different</p><p>(a) $\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{2}}$ is water soluble and undergoes slow oxidative hydrolysis.</p><p>$2\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{2}}+2{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}\\xrightarrow{{}}2\\text{Xe}+{{\\text{O}}_{2}}+4\\text{HF}$</p><p>(b) $\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{4}}$ reacts with water violently to give $\\text{Xe}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}$</p><p>$3\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{4}}+6{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}\\xrightarrow{{}}2\\text{Xe}+\\text{Xe}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}+\\frac{3}{2}{{\\text{O}}_{2}}+12\\text{HF}$</p><p>In this reaction $\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{4}}$ disproportionates and ${{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}$ is parthy oxidized.</p><p>(c) $\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{6}}$ also reacts violently to give $\\text{Xe}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}$</p><p>$\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{6}}+6{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}\\xrightarrow{{}}\\text{Xe}{{\\text{O}}_{4}}+12\\text{HF}$</p><p>With small amount of water</p><p>$\\text{Xe}{{\\text{F}}_{6}}+{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}\\xrightarrow{{}}\\text{XeO}{{\\text{F}}_{4}}+2\\text{HF}$</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dccec03b9dcaf1afe7c6"
    }
  ],
